ShortSummary: An abrasion is a wound caused by superficial damage to the skin, usually due to a scrape or friction.
An abscess is a localized collection of pus in a cavity formed by the disintegration of tissues.
Achilles tendinitis is characterized by pain and inflammation of the Achilles tendon, typically due to overuse.

Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder is characterised by a persistent pattern (at least 6 months) of inattention and/or hyperactivity-impulsivity that has a direct negative impact on academic, occupational, or social functioning.
Airway obstruction is a blockage in any part of the airway that impedes breathing.
Alcohol intolerance is a condition in which the body cannot break down alcohol properly, often due to a genetic variant.
Allergic asthma is asthma triggered by exposure to allergens such as pollen, dust mites, or pet dander.
Allergic conjunctivitis is inflammation of the conjunctiva caused by an allergic reaction to substances like pollen or mold.
An allergic reaction is an immune system response to a foreign substance that's not typically harmful to your body.
Allergic rhinitis is an allergic reaction that causes sneezing, congestion, and a runny nose.
Alzheimer’s disease is a progressive neurodegenerative disorder that causes memory loss, cognitive decline, and behavioral changes.
An anal fissure is a small tear in the lining of the anus which can cause pain and bleeding during bowel movements.
Anaphylaxis is a severe, potentially life-threatening allergic reaction that occurs rapidly after exposure to an allergen.
Anemia is a condition in which the blood doesn’t have enough healthy red blood cells or hemoglobin.
Angina is chest pain or discomfort due to reduced blood flow to the heart muscle.
An ankle sprain is an injury to the ligaments that connect bones in the ankle, often due to twisting.
Anorexia nervosa is an eating disorder characterized by weight loss, food restriction, and an intense fear of gaining weight.
Anxiety is a feeling of worry, nervousness, or unease about something with an uncertain outcome.
An anxiety disorder involves excessive fear or anxiety that interferes with daily activities.
Aphthous stomatitis is a common condition characterized by the repeated formation of benign and non-contagious mouth ulcers.
Appendicitis is a condition characterized by inflammation of the vermiform appendix, which may become obstructed and infected.
Arrhythmia is a group of conditions in which the heartbeat is irregular, too fast, or too slow.
Arthritis is a group of diseases that cause inflammation and degeneration of joints.
Asthma is a chronic inflammatory disorder of the airways characterised by recurrent episodes of wheezing, breathlessness, chest tightness and coughing.
Autism spectrum disorder is characterised by persistent deficits in the ability to initiate and sustain reciprocal social interaction and social communication.
Autoimmune urticaria is a form of chronic hives that occurs when the body's immune system attacks its own tissues.
Bacterial vaginosis is a condition characterised by an overgrowth of certain bacteria in the vagina, resulting in an imbalance of the normal vaginal flora.
Bell's palsy is an acute peripheral facial nerve palsy of unknown cause resulting in muscle weakness on one side of the face.
Benign paroxysmal positional vertigo is a condition characterised by brief episodes of vertigo associated with changes in head position.
Bipolar disorder is characterised by episodes of elevated mood and increased activity or energy (mania or hypomania) and episodes of depression.
Bladder cancer is a malignant neoplasm arising from the epithelial lining of the urinary bladder.
Blepharitis is an inflammatory condition affecting the eyelid margins, often associated with bacterial infection or skin conditions.
Blistering skin disorders are a group of conditions characterised by blister formation on the skin and mucous membranes.
Borderline personality disorder is characterised by a pervasive pattern of instability in interpersonal relationships, self-image, and affect, with marked impulsivity.
Bowel cancer, also known as colorectal cancer, develops when cells in the wall of the large bowel grow in an abnormal and uncontrolled way.
Brain injury refers to damage to the brain that impairs its normal function and can result from trauma or other causes.
A brain tumour is an abnormal growth of tissue in the brain that can be benign or malignant.
Breast cancer is a malignant tumour that originates from the breast tissue, most commonly from the lining of the milk ducts.
Breast cysts are fluid-filled sacs within the breast, often benign and related to hormonal changes.
Bronchitis is an inflammation of the bronchial tubes, often resulting from infection and characterised by coughing and sputum production.
Burns are injuries to tissues caused by heat, electricity, chemicals, or radiation, classified by depth and severity.
Bursitis is inflammation of the bursa, a small fluid-filled sac that cushions bones, tendons, and muscles near joints.
Cancer is a group of diseases characterised by the uncontrolled growth and spread of abnormal cells.
Carcinoid syndrome is a condition caused by hormone-secreting carcinoid tumors, leading to symptoms such as flushing and diarrhea.
Carpal tunnel syndrome is a condition caused by compression of the median nerve within the carpal tunnel of the wrist, resulting in pain and numbness.
A cataract is a clouding of the eye's natural lens, leading to blurred vision and visual impairment.
Cellulitis is a common bacterial skin infection that causes redness, swelling, and pain in the affected area.
Cervical spondylosis is a degenerative condition of the cervical spine due to wear and tear of bones and discs.
Chemical burns result from skin or eye contact with corrosive substances such as acids or alkalis, leading to tissue damage.
Chickenpox is a highly contagious disease caused by the varicella-zoster virus, characterised by an itchy rash and fever.
Chronic fatigue syndrome is a complex disorder characterised by extreme fatigue that is not improved by rest and may worsen with physical or mental activity.
Chronic illness refers to long-lasting conditions that often require ongoing medical attention and affect daily living.
Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease is a progressive lung disease that obstructs airflow and makes breathing difficult.
Chronic pain is persistent or recurrent pain lasting longer than three months and may arise from a variety of causes.
The common cold is a viral upper respiratory tract infection that causes symptoms such as runny nose, cough, and sore throat.
Concussion is a type of traumatic brain injury caused by a blow to the head, leading to temporary loss of brain function.
Congenital heart disease encompasses a range of defects in the heart's structure and function present from birth.
Conjunctivitis is inflammation of the conjunctiva, causing redness, discharge, and irritation of the eye.
Constipation is a common digestive issue characterised by infrequent bowel movements or difficulty passing stools.
Contact dermatitis is an inflammatory skin reaction resulting from direct contact with allergens or irritants.
Contusion, or bruise, is a type of hematoma caused by trauma to tissues without breaking the skin, leading to discoloration.
Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease is a common, preventable, and treatable disease characterised by persistent respiratory symptoms and airflow limitation.
Corneal abrasion is a scratch or injury to the surface layer of the eye, causing pain, redness, and tearing.
Coronary artery disease is a condition in which narrowed arteries reduce blood flow to the heart muscle.
COVID-19 is an infectious disease caused by the SARS-CoV-2 virus, primarily affecting the respiratory system and ranging from mild symptoms to severe illness.
Cushing’s syndrome is caused by prolonged exposure to high cortisol levels, leading to symptoms like weight gain and high blood pressure.
Cyanosis is a bluish discoloration of the skin and mucous membranes due to low oxygen levels in the blood.
Deep vein thrombosis is the formation of a blood clot in a deep vein, usually in the legs, which can be life-threatening if it travels to the lungs.
Dehydration occurs when the body loses more fluids than it takes in, leading to impaired normal body functions.
Delirium is an acute neuropsychiatric syndrome characterised by disturbed consciousness, attention, and cognition.
Dementia is a syndrome resulting in deterioration in memory, thinking, behavior, and the ability to perform everyday activities.
A dental abscess is a localized collection of pus in the tissues surrounding a tooth, usually due to bacterial infection.
Depression is a common mental disorder characterised by persistent sadness, loss of interest, and impairment in daily functioning.
Dermatitis refers to inflammation of the skin characterized by redness, swelling, and itching.
A deviated septum is when the cartilage and bone that divides your nose down the middle is not straight.
Diabetes is a chronic disease characterized by elevated levels of blood glucose resulting from defects in insulin production, action, or both.
Diabetic retinopathy is a microvascular complication of diabetes that affects the retina, leading to vision impairment.
Diuretic use refers to the administration of medications that promote the excretion of salt and water from the body to treat various conditions like hypertension.
Drug allergy is an adverse immune response to a medication, which can manifest as skin reactions, respiratory symptoms, or anaphylaxis.
Drug overdose occurs when a person takes more than the medically recommended dose of a drug, leading to toxic effects or death.
Dry eye syndrome is a multifactorial disease of the ocular surface characterized by loss of tear film homeostasis and ocular symptoms.
Dysmenorrhea is characterized by painful menstrual cramps originating from the uterus before or during menstruation.
Ear barotrauma is damage to the ear caused by pressure differences between the inside and outside of the eardrum.
Earwax buildup refers to the accumulation of cerumen that can block the ear canal and affect hearing.
Ectopic pregnancy is a condition in which a fertilized egg implants outside the uterine cavity, most commonly in the fallopian tube.
Eczema is a group of conditions that cause the skin to become inflamed, itchy, and cracked, often due to genetic and environmental factors.
An electrical burn results from contact with electric current, which can cause deep tissue damage and cardiac complications.
Electrolyte imbalance refers to abnormal levels of essential minerals like sodium, potassium, and calcium that affect various body functions.
Endometrial cancer is a malignancy originating from the lining of the uterus, commonly presenting with abnormal uterine bleeding.
Endometriosis is a chronic inflammatory condition where tissue similar to the endometrium grows outside the uterus, causing pain and infertility.
Envenomation refers to the process by which venom is injected into a person through a bite or sting by a venomous animal.
Epilepsy is a brain disorder characterized by recurrent, unprovoked seizures due to abnormal electrical activity in the brain.
Esophageal injury involves damage to the esophagus, which may result from trauma, ingestion of corrosives, or medical procedures.
Esophageal varices are abnormally dilated veins in the lower esophagus, often due to portal hypertension and risk of life-threatening bleeding.
Essential tremor is a neurological disorder that causes rhythmic trembling of the hands, head, voice, or other body parts during voluntary movements.
Exercise-induced asthma is the narrowing of the airways triggered by vigorous physical activity, causing coughing, wheezing, or shortness of breath.
Facial fracture refers to any break in the bones of the face, such as the nose, jaw, or cheekbones, typically due to trauma.
Febrile seizures are convulsions triggered by fever in infants and young children, typically occurring without an underlying neurological cause.
A fibroadenoma is a benign breast tumor composed of fibrous and glandular tissue, commonly found in young women.
Fibroids are benign tumors of the uterus composed of smooth muscle and connective tissue, often associated with heavy menstrual bleeding.
Influenza (flu) is a contagious respiratory illness caused by influenza viruses, characterized by fever, cough, body aches, and fatigue.
Food allergy is an immune system reaction to a specific food, leading to symptoms that range from mild rash to anaphylaxis.
Food poisoning is an illness caused by consuming contaminated food or drinks, leading to symptoms such as vomiting, diarrhea, and stomach cramps.
A foreign body in the eye refers to any object—dust, metal, or glass—that enters and causes irritation or injury to the eye surface.
Foreign body ingestion occurs when an object is swallowed accidentally, potentially causing obstruction or injury to the gastrointestinal tract.
A foreign object in the ear occurs when items like beads or insects enter the ear canal, leading to discomfort, pain, or hearing loss.
A fracture is a break or crack in a bone usually resulting from trauma, overuse, or disease conditions like osteoporosis.
A friction blister is a fluid-filled skin lesion caused by repetitive rubbing, commonly occurring on the hands or feet.
Galactorrhea is the spontaneous flow of milk from the breast, unrelated to childbirth or nursing, often due to hormonal imbalances.
Gastritis is the inflammation of the stomach lining, usually caused by infection, certain medications, or excessive alcohol consumption.
Gastroenteritis is inflammation of the stomach and intestines, often caused by viral or bacterial infection, leading to diarrhea and vomiting.
Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD) happens when stomach acid leaks into your food pipe, causing symptoms or health complications.
Generalized anxiety disorder is characterized by excessive, uncontrollable worry about various aspects of life, lasting for at least six months.
Geographic tongue is a benign condition with irregular, red patches on the tongue surface, giving it a map-like appearance.
Gingivitis is a mild form of gum disease causing redness, swelling, and bleeding, often due to poor oral hygiene.
Glaucoma is a group of eye diseases that damage the optic nerve, often due to elevated intraocular pressure, potentially leading to blindness.
Gout is a type of arthritis characterized by sudden, severe attacks of pain, redness, and swelling in joints, due to uric acid buildup.
Head injury refers to trauma to the head that may affect the scalp, skull, or brain, ranging from mild bumps to serious brain damage.
Hearing loss is a partial or total inability to hear, resulting from damage to the ear or auditory nerves.
A heart attack occurs when blood flow to the heart muscle is blocked, usually by a clot, leading to tissue damage.
Heart failure is a chronic condition in which the heart is unable to pump blood effectively to meet the body’s needs.
Heat rash is a skin irritation caused by blocked sweat ducts, resulting in small red bumps and discomfort in hot or humid conditions.
Hemorrhoids are swollen veins in the lower rectum or anus that cause discomfort, bleeding, or itching.
A herniated disc occurs when the soft center of a spinal disc pushes through a crack in the tougher exterior, potentially compressing nearby nerves.
Herpes simplex is a viral infection causing sores on the mouth or genitals, typically caused by HSV-1 or HSV-2.
Hormonal imbalance occurs when there's too much or too little of a hormone, disrupting body functions like metabolism, reproduction, and mood.
Horner's syndrome is a rare neurological disorder characterized by drooping eyelid, pupil constriction, and reduced sweating on one side of the face.
Hypercalcemia is a condition in which calcium levels in the blood are above normal, often caused by overactive parathyroid glands or cancer.
Hypertension, or high blood pressure, is a chronic condition in which the force of blood against artery walls is consistently too high.
Hyperthyroidism is a condition where the thyroid gland produces excessive hormones, leading to increased metabolism and other symptoms.
Hypoglycemia is a condition characterized by abnormally low levels of blood glucose, which can lead to shakiness, confusion, or fainting.
Hypoxia is a condition where the body or a part of the body is deprived of adequate oxygen supply at the tissue level.
Infection occurs when harmful microorganisms invade the body, multiply, and cause illness or inflammation.
An injury is physical damage to the body caused by external force, ranging from minor cuts to serious trauma.
Insomnia is a sleep disorder characterized by difficulty falling asleep, staying asleep, or getting restful sleep.
Intracranial hemorrhage is bleeding within the skull, often caused by trauma, stroke, or ruptured aneurysms.
Irritable bowel syndrome is a functional gastrointestinal disorder marked by chronic abdominal pain and altered bowel habits.
Jock itch is a fungal skin infection that affects the groin area, causing redness, itching, and a ring-shaped rash.
Kidney failure is a condition where the kidneys lose their ability to filter waste and balance fluids in the body.
A kidney stone is a hard mineral deposit formed in the kidneys, often causing severe pain during passage through the urinary tract.
A laceration is a deep cut or tear in the skin or flesh, often caused by blunt or sharp trauma.
Lactose intolerance is the inability to digest lactose, a sugar found in milk, leading to gastrointestinal discomfort.
Learning disabilities affect how you learn in a specific area, such as reading or writing.
Leukemia is a type of cancer that affects blood-forming tissues, leading to the overproduction of abnormal white blood cells.
A ligament injury involves damage to the tough bands of tissue connecting bones, often caused by excessive force or twisting.
A ligament sprain is the overstretching or tearing of ligaments, typically resulting from sudden twists or trauma.
A lipoma is a benign tumor composed of fatty tissue, usually soft and movable under the skin.
Low blood pressure, or hypotension, is when blood pressure drops below the normal range, possibly causing dizziness or fainting.
A low fiber diet restricts the intake of dietary fiber, often used to manage specific digestive or post-operative conditions.
Low sperm count is a condition where the semen contains fewer sperm than normal, which can affect male fertility.
Lung cancer is a malignant tumor in the lungs characterized by uncontrolled cell growth, often related to smoking.
A lung contusion is a bruise of the lung tissue, usually caused by trauma, leading to bleeding and swelling.
Lymphadenopathy is the abnormal enlargement of lymph nodes, often due to infection, autoimmune disease, or malignancy.
Lymphedema is swelling caused by lymph fluid buildup, usually in the arms or legs, due to blockage or damage.
Lymphoma is a cancer of the lymphatic system, which includes lymph nodes, spleen, and bone marrow.
Major depressive disorder is a mood disorder characterized by persistent sadness, loss of interest, and impaired daily functioning.
Malabsorption is a disorder in which the small intestine cannot absorb nutrients properly, leading to nutritional deficiencies.
Malnutrition refers to deficiencies, excesses, or imbalances in energy and nutrient intake affecting health and development.
Mastitis is inflammation of breast tissue, often due to infection, resulting in pain, swelling, and redness.
Meniere's disease is a chronic inner ear disorder causing vertigo, hearing loss, tinnitus, and a feeling of fullness in the ear.
Meningitis is an inflammation of the protective membranes covering the brain and spinal cord, often caused by infection.
A meniscus tear is an injury to the cartilage in the knee, often caused by twisting motions or trauma.
Menopause is the natural cessation of menstruation, marked by hormonal changes and the end of reproductive capability in women.
Migraine is a neurological condition characterized by recurrent, often severe headaches, typically accompanied by nausea and sensitivity to light or sound.
Mild traumatic brain injury, often referred to as a concussion, is a brain injury resulting from a blow or jolt to the head.
Miliaria, or heat rash, occurs when sweat ducts become blocked, leading to skin irritation and small red bumps.
Molar pregnancy is a rare complication of pregnancy characterized by abnormal growth of trophoblasts, the cells that normally develop into the placenta.
Motion sickness is a disturbance of the inner ear caused by repeated motion, leading to nausea, dizziness, and vomiting.
A mouth ulcer is a small, painful sore inside the mouth, often caused by injury, stress, or certain conditions.
Multiple sclerosis is a chronic autoimmune disease where the immune system attacks the central nervous system, leading to varied neurological symptoms.
A muscle spasm is a sudden, involuntary contraction of one or more muscles, often causing pain or stiffness.
Muscle strain is an injury where muscle fibers are overstretched or torn, often due to physical overexertion.
Nasal trauma refers to injury to the nose, which may cause bleeding, swelling, deformity, or breathing difficulty.
Nerve damage is an injury or dysfunction of nerves resulting in numbness, weakness, or pain in affected areas.
Nerve injury involves trauma or compression that disrupts nerve signals, potentially causing motor or sensory dysfunction.
Obsessive compulsive disorder is a mental health condition characterized by intrusive thoughts (obsessions) and repetitive behaviors (compulsions).
Occupational asthma is asthma caused or worsened by inhaling fumes, gases, dust, or other harmful substances in the workplace.
Opioid overdose occurs when excessive use of opioids suppresses breathing, potentially leading to unconsciousness or death.
Optic neuritis is inflammation of the optic nerve, often associated with pain and temporary vision loss.
An orbital fracture is a break in one of the bones surrounding the eye, typically caused by blunt trauma to the face.
Osteoarthritis is a degenerative joint disease characterized by cartilage breakdown, causing joint pain and stiffness.
Otitis media is an inflammation or infection of the middle ear, often causing ear pain, fever, and hearing problems.
Overflow incontinence is the involuntary release of urine due to an overfilled bladder that doesn't empty properly.
A panic attack is a sudden episode of intense fear or anxiety accompanied by physical symptoms like rapid heartbeat or shortness of breath.
Panic disorder is characterized by recurring panic attacks and persistent worry about having future attacks.
Parkinson's disease is a progressive neurological disorder characterized by tremor, rigidity, and bradykinesia due to dopamine deficiency.
Pelvic inflammatory disease is an infection of the female reproductive organs, often caused by sexually transmitted bacteria.
A peptic ulcer is a sore in the stomach lining or upper part of the small intestine caused by stomach acid and H. pylori infection.
Perimenopause is the transitional period before menopause when hormonal fluctuations cause irregular periods and other symptoms.
Periodontitis is a serious gum infection that damages the soft tissue and can destroy the bone that supports your teeth.
Peripheral artery disease is a condition where narrowed arteries reduce blood flow to the limbs, typically causing leg pain during walking.
Peripheral neuropathy is damage to the peripheral nerves causing weakness, numbness, and pain, typically in the hands and feet.
Persistent depressive disorder is a chronic form of depression with long-term symptoms that are less severe but longer lasting.
Pharyngitis is inflammation of the pharynx, resulting in a sore throat and discomfort when swallowing.
Photosensitivity is an abnormal skin reaction to sunlight or artificial light, often due to medications or underlying conditions.
A pinched nerve occurs when surrounding tissues compress a nerve, causing pain, tingling, or numbness.
Pinworms are small intestinal parasites that cause itching around the anus, especially at night.
Piriformis syndrome is a condition in which the piriformis muscle irritates or compresses the sciatic nerve, causing pain in the buttocks and leg.
Pneumonia is an infection that inflames the air sacs in one or both lungs, which may fill with fluid or pus.
Pneumothorax is the presence of air in the pleural space causing lung collapse and difficulty breathing.
Poisoning happens when you are sufficiently exposed to a substance that can cause illness, injury or death.
Polycystic ovary syndrome is a hormonal disorder causing enlarged ovaries with small cysts, irregular periods, and excess androgens.
A pontine stroke is a type of brainstem stroke affecting the pons, which can lead to severe motor, speech, and sensory deficits.
Post-concussion syndrome is a complex disorder with symptoms like headache and dizziness lasting weeks or months after a concussion.
Pregnancy is the condition of having a developing embryo or fetus within the body, typically lasting about 40 weeks in humans.
Primary nocturnal enuresis is involuntary urination during sleep in children aged five years or older who have never been consistently dry at night.
Proctitis is inflammation of the lining of the rectum, which can cause rectal pain, bleeding, and a frequent urge to defecate.
Psoriasis is a chronic autoimmune skin disease that speeds up the life cycle of skin cells, leading to scaling and inflammation.
Psoriatic arthritis is a chronic inflammatory arthritis associated with psoriasis, causing joint pain, stiffness, and swelling.
Psychogenic polydipsia is a condition characterized by excessive water intake due to psychological factors, often seen in psychiatric patients.
Post-traumatic stress disorder is a mental health condition triggered by experiencing or witnessing a traumatic event.
Pubic lice are tiny parasites that infest the hair in the pubic area, causing itching and irritation.
Pulmonary embolism is a blockage in one of the pulmonary arteries in the lungs, usually caused by blood clots that travel from the legs.
A puncture wound is a deep wound caused by a sharp, pointed object that pierces the skin and underlying tissues.
Rabies is a viral disease that affects the central nervous system and is almost always fatal once symptoms appear.
Raynaud’s phenomenon is a condition in which small blood vessels in the fingers and toes constrict in response to cold or stress, causing color changes and pain.
Refractive error is a common eye disorder where the eye does not bend light properly, resulting in blurred vision.
Respiratory distress is a condition where breathing becomes difficult and inefficient, often requiring immediate medical attention.
Respiratory infection refers to any infectious disease involving the respiratory tract, such as bronchitis, pneumonia, or the common cold.
Rheumatoid arthritis is an autoimmune disorder that primarily affects joints, causing pain, swelling, and eventually joint damage.
A rib fracture is a break or crack in one of the bones in the rib cage, typically caused by trauma or injury.
A rotator cuff tear is an injury to the group of muscles and tendons that stabilize the shoulder joint and allow arm movement.
Scarlet fever is a bacterial illness that develops in some people with strep throat and is characterized by a red rash and high fever.
Schizophrenia is a chronic mental disorder characterized by distorted thinking, hallucinations, delusions, and impaired functioning.
Sciatica refers to pain that radiates along the path of the sciatic nerve, usually caused by compression or irritation of the nerve roots.
Sepsis is a life-threatening organ dysfunction caused by a dysregulated body response to infection.
Severe illness in infants can include conditions that lead to critical health deterioration requiring urgent medical attention.
Sexually transmitted infections are infections transmitted through sexual contact, caused by bacteria, viruses, or parasites.
Shock is a critical condition brought on by a sudden drop in blood flow through the body, which can be life-threatening.
Sinusitis is inflammation or swelling of the tissue lining the sinuses, often due to infection, causing congestion and facial pain.
Skin cancer is the abnormal growth of skin cells, usually caused by ultraviolet radiation from the sun or tanning beds.
A staph skin infection happens when staphylococcus bacteria get inside your body and affects your skin.
Skin irritation is a general term for redness, itching, or burning caused by contact with an irritant or allergen.
A skull fracture is a break in the cranial bone resulting from head trauma and may be accompanied by brain injury.
Sleep deprivation occurs when an individual gets insufficient sleep, leading to fatigue, cognitive impairment, and other health issues.
Social anxiety disorder is a mental health condition characterized by intense fear or anxiety in social situations.
Social behaviour disorders affect a person's ability to manage their behaviour in a positive way.
Spinal stenosis is the narrowing of spaces in the spine, which can put pressure on the spinal cord and nerves.
Spontaneous abortion, also known as miscarriage, is the natural loss of a pregnancy before the 20th week.
A sprain is a stretch or tear of ligaments caused by sudden twisting or force to a joint.
Stable angina is chest pain or discomfort that typically occurs with activity or stress due to reduced blood flow to the heart.
A stroke occurs when the blood supply to part of the brain is interrupted or reduced, causing brain cells to die.
Sunburn is skin damage caused by overexposure to ultraviolet rays from the sun, resulting in redness and pain.
Swallowed foreign object refers to the accidental ingestion of non-food items, which may require medical attention depending on the object and symptoms.
Swimmer’s ear is an outer ear canal infection often caused by water remaining in the ear, creating a moist environment for bacteria.
Temporomandibular joint disorder involves pain and dysfunction in the jaw joint and muscles controlling jaw movement.
Tendonitis is the inflammation of a tendon, typically caused by repetitive motion or overuse, resulting in pain and limited mobility.
Tension headache is a common type of headache characterized by a dull, aching pain and tightness across the forehead or back of the head.
Tetanus is a serious bacterial infection characterized by muscle stiffness and spasms, often caused by wounds contaminated with Clostridium tetani.
A thermal burn is tissue damage caused by contact with hot objects, flames, steam, or scalding liquids.
Thrombocytopenia is when you have low levels of platelets in your blood.
Thyroid disorders include conditions affecting the thyroid gland, leading to overproduction or underproduction of thyroid hormones.
Tonsillitis is inflammation of the tonsils, usually due to viral or bacterial infection, causing sore throat and difficulty swallowing.
A tooth abscess is a localized bacterial infection in the tooth or gums, often causing pain, swelling, and pus.
A transient ischemic attack (TIA) is a temporary period of stroke-like symptoms caused by brief blockage of blood flow to the brain.
Traumatic brain injury is damage to the brain resulting from external mechanical force, often leading to physical, cognitive, or emotional impairment.
Tuberculosis is a bacterial infection caused by Mycobacterium tuberculosis, primarily affecting the lungs and potentially spreading to other organs.
Unstable angina is a type of chest pain that occurs unpredictably and may signal an impending heart attack.
Upper gastrointestinal bleeding refers to bleeding from the esophagus, stomach, or the first part of the small intestine, often presenting as vomiting blood.
An upper respiratory infection affects the nose, throat, and airways, commonly caused by viruses leading to symptoms like cough, congestion, and sore throat.
Urge incontinence is a sudden, intense urge to urinate followed by involuntary leakage, often due to overactive bladder muscles.
A urinary tract infection (UTI) is a bacterial infection affecting any part of the urinary system, most commonly the bladder and urethra.
Urinary tract obstruction is a blockage that inhibits the flow of urine, potentially leading to kidney damage if left untreated.
Uveitis is inflammation of the uvea, the middle layer of the eye, which can cause redness, pain, light sensitivity, and blurred vision.
Vaginitis is inflammation of the vagina, often due to infection, hormonal changes, or irritants, leading to discharge, itching, and discomfort.
Vasovagal syncope is a common cause of fainting, triggered by sudden drops in heart rate and blood pressure, often due to stress or standing too long.
A venous ulcer is a chronic wound on the leg caused by poor blood circulation due to venous insufficiency.
A vertebral fracture is a break in a spinal bone, often caused by trauma or osteoporosis, resulting in pain and limited mobility.
Vertigo is a sensation of spinning or dizziness, often caused by inner ear problems affecting balance.
Vestibular neuritis is inflammation of the vestibular nerve, leading to sudden, severe vertigo without hearing loss.
Viral exanthem is a widespread skin rash caused by a viral infection, often accompanied by fever and other systemic symptoms.
A viral upper respiratory infection is a common viral illness affecting the nose and throat, leading to sneezing, sore throat, and cough.
Vitamin C deficiency, or scurvy, is a condition resulting from inadequate intake of vitamin C, leading to fatigue, bleeding gums, and poor wound healing.
Vitamin deficiency refers to insufficient levels of essential vitamins, which can cause various health problems depending on the vitamin lacking.
A yeast infection is a fungal infection caused by Candida species, commonly affecting moist areas like the mouth, skin folds, or vagina.
